			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">There have been many questions regarding the change in the recycling and selling magically enhanced items.  Lietgardis, one of the Designers on Shadowbane, tackles this subject.
<br />

<br />
The new "formula" item creation scheme in Throne of Oblivion required a lot of changes to the old item rolling system, an old, unintuitive, clunker of a system.  We still wanted to keep the old system around for guilds that couldn't capture mines or afford to trade for resources, but we had to modify some aspects.  Here's why.
<br />

<br />
Previously, shop owners weren't charged for items until they were completed.  The price of the item depended on the enchantments it was blessed with, so naturally, the vendor wouldn't know what to charge until it was done.
<br />

<br />
With the new formula system, shop owners know exactly what they're getting from the beginning.  But in testing, we found that if the resource cost was charged at the end, same as in the old rolling system, it was possible for multiple items to be created at different shops with the same price, and if the warehouse didn't have enough to cover them all, only the first one could be completed.  The other shop owners would be left with an uncompletable item until the warehouse's stores were refilled.  This sucked.
<br />

<br />
In reaction, we decided to change the underlying architecture of the item creation system to charge for items up front.  This caused a problem with the old rolling system, though - if the shop owner knows the gold value of the item before it's completed, she can make a reasonable guess about the enchantments it carries, and she can choose to junk it.  And if it's a crappy, but expensive item, she's out all that gold.  Most enchantments have hefty +value modifiers.
<br />

<br />
As a service to shop owners, we chose to have vendors charge the base cost plus 10%, rather than the full value of the item.  Junking the items or selling them back will give the owner the base cost.
<br />

<br />
In the future, we hope that most items are crafted through the formula system.  We hope that guilds continue to fight for mines, and trade for resources so their members can get the items they want.  There won't be a disappointing crapshoot for subpar equipment.  And we hope that resources gain enough trade value to make up for the loss of gold income.  We hope you like it.
<br />

<br />
- Lietgardis.
<br />

<br />
In addition, we have a variety of changes coming in with a mini-patch to include a fix for crafting multiple items using the "Magic" system.  Beaker, the lead UI programmer, has changed the crafting system to be more end-user friendly.   Here is a screenshot on how the new Crafting Interface will look:
<br />

<br />
<img src="http://chronicle.ubi.com/NR/rdonlyres/eerguacn76doibbeipjbg2odl4hlkkfctdzzdrgf3hhfw2qiplslchjagbowq6l2pgijoej235qyvh/ItemCreation.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
You'll note that you no longer have to click on an empty slot to craft an item but instead click one of the buttons to the side.  Take notice of the Create Multiple Items button; this basically works as a mass produce and will fill all available slots with the item you wish to craft.  Another minor change leaves the creation window open so players can make tweaks without having to reopen the crafting interface.  Now to create a variety of Ring Blades using the Formula System, you can leave the interface open after submitting an order for a Morloch's Ring Blade of Oblivion and just change the Suffix to 'of Dispatch' and have a new order underway without opening another window or going through all the tabs again.  Finally, many of the additional pop-ups have been removed to lessen the amount of mouse clicks end-users have to go through.
<br />

<br />
By: Ashen Temper             -             Official News 12/14/2004 7:39:23 PM
